   <abstract >In the theory of wave propagation, several important nonlinear dispersive systems are known to be integrable – that is, exactly solvable by linear techniques. Such systems are typically characterized by the existence of an infinite number of conserved quantities, a Hamiltonian structure, the admittance of soliton solutions, and many other rich mathematical properties. The primary focus of this thesis is a study of integrable systems that are nonlocal in the sense that they possess a reflected and shifted spatial and/or temporal argument. Chapter 1 serves as an informal overview of the field of integrable partial differential equations and an introduction to this nonlocal variety. Chapter 2 provides a detailed analysis of the solution process, known as the inverse scattering transform (IST) method, for several examples of nonlocal integrable systems. The IST is developed and solutions are constructed for nonlocal variants of the nonlinear Schrödinger (NLS) equation, the modified Korteweg-de Vries (mKdV) equation, and the semi-discrete Ablowitz-Ladik (AL) lattice. The secondary subject of this thesis is beam propagation in non-Hermitian optical media. In this context, non-Hermiticity refers to the presence of a complex-valued index of refraction, where the imaginary part is interpreted as a distribution of gain and loss of power (which in this case in not conserved). Such systems have been shown (theoretically and experimentally) to possess many counter-intuitive properties, one of which is the existence of constant-intensity (CI) waves that can propagate through the medium without diffracting. In Chapter 3, special types of these CI waves are introduced and their properties and further implications, including their usefulness in the study of dispersive hydrodynamics in non-Hermitian media, are discussed. These two topics are unified by the fact that they both center around NLS-type models in which certain fundamental properties such as conservation of power and translational invariance are lost. In the latter case, this is due to a complex external potential, while in the former case this is due to a nonlocal self-induced potential.</abstract>
